# Global AI Assistant Rules

Every time you generate, modify, or review code, strictly adhere to the following rules — no exceptions, no need for the user to re-ask.

---

## 1. File Size & Splitting (Critical)
- **Hard limit: 200 lines per file.** If a file exceeds this, split it immediately.
- Extract sub-components, hooks, utilities, or constants into separate files before the file grows — don't wait until it's already large.
- Never dump multiple components, types, or logic blocks into a single file.
- If adding code will push a file over the limit, refactor first, then add.

## 2. Codebase Cleanup
- Continuously refactor alongside any feature development — don't defer cleanup.
- Remove unused imports, dead code, commented-out snippets, and stray `console.log`s.
- Simplify complex logic wherever a cleaner equivalent exists.

## 3. Strict Best Practices (Next.js / React / TypeScript)
- Follow App Router conventions strictly — no mixing of Pages Router patterns.
- Separate Server and Client components clearly; default to Server unless interactivity requires Client (`"use client"` only where necessary).
- Enable and respect strict TypeScript — no `any`, no type suppression without a comment explaining why.
- Always handle errors and edge cases explicitly; never silently swallow errors.

## 4. Folder Structure
- `src/components/` → shared/reusable UI components only.
- `src/features/<feature>/` → feature-specific components, hooks, and logic (co-located).
- `src/hooks/` → shared custom hooks.
- `src/lib/` or `src/utils/` → utilities, helpers, constants.
- `src/types/` → shared TypeScript types and interfaces.
- API routes stay inside `src/app/api/`.
- **Never** place utility/helper files in the root or inside `app/` directly.

## 5. Code Quality
- Write DRY, modular, single-responsibility code.
- One component = one file = one clear purpose.
- Prefer named exports over default exports (easier refactoring, better autocomplete).
- Add comments only for non-obvious logic — not for self-explanatory code.
- Avoid prop drilling more than 2 levels deep — use context or state management instead.

## 6. Component Design
- Keep components purely presentational where possible; lift logic into hooks.
- Extract repeated JSX blocks (even 2+ times) into a sub-component.
- Avoid inline styles; use Tailwind classes or CSS modules consistently.

---

Treat these as the highest-priority constraints for every task in this workspace.
